'''Liliana Betti'''  (1937 – 19 August 1998) was an Italian screenwriter and director. She was sometimes credited as '''Liliane Betti'''.

Born in [[Corte Franca|Nigoline]], [[Province of Brescia]], Betti in 1957 moved to [[Rome]], where she became a real life friend of [[Federico Fellini]].<ref name="la re">{{cite news|last1=Michele Tavola|title=Fellini disegna la sua musa ispiratrice|url=http://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/2008/07/27/fellini-disegna-la-sua-musa-ispiratrice.html?ref=search|accessdate=17 November 2014|newspaper=[[La Repubblica]]|date=27 July 2008|page=14}}</ref><ref name=corr>{{cite news|title=E' morta Liliana Betti assistente di Fellini|newspaper=[[Corriere della Sera]]|date=21 August 1998|page=29}}</ref> Fellini referred to her as "her boss" and as "the little goddess of ideas", and Betti was a collaborator, a casting director, a script supervisor and a second unit director for many of his films until 1980.<ref name="la re" /> As a screenwriter, she also often collaborated with [[Marco Ferreri]] and [[Enrico Oldoini]].<ref name=corr /> In 1991 she was nominated at the [[David di Donatello|David di Donatello Award]] for [[David di Donatello for Best Script|best screenplay]] for Ferreri's ''[[The House of Smiles]]''.

